      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is 8 glasses of water per day accurate?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">The "8 glasses a day" rule (approximately 2 litres) is a rough population average that has no specific scientific basis as a universal target. The origin is often traced to a 1945 US Food and Nutrition Board recommendation that was widely misinterpreted. Actual needs vary significantly by body weight, climate, activity level, and diet. For a 60 kg sedentary person, 8 glasses may be adequate. For an 80 kg person exercising in a hot climate, it may be significantly insufficient. Weight-based calculation (35 ml/kg) is more accurate for most adults.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How can I tell if I am drinking enough water?</button>
        <div class="faq-a">Urine colour is the most practical real-world indicator of hydration status. Pale straw yellow (like lemonade) indicates good hydration. Bright or dark yellow indicates mild-to-moderate dehydration. Clear urine may indicate over-hydration. Other signs of adequate hydration include infrequent thirst, normal energy levels, and urinating 4–8 times per day. Urine colour is affected by vitamins (B vitamins cause bright yellow regardless of hydration) and some foods (beetroot causes pink/red). Use our <a href="water-intake.html">Water Intake Calculator</a> for a personalised daily target.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-callout"><p>⚠️ This guide is for general informational purposes. People with kidney disease, heart failure, or other conditions affecting fluid balance should follow their doctor's specific guidance, which may differ from standard recommendations.</p></div>

